. These textual terms are multilingual and can be displayed in any language.  \n\n- **Properties** – predicates that define the kind of information a statement can hold, each identified by a P‑number (e.g., educated\u202fat\u202fP69).  \n\n- **Statements** – the factual data attached to an item. A statement is a **property–value** pair (e.g., Q42\u202fP69\u202fQ691283 = “Douglas\u202fAdams educated at St\u202fJohn’s\u202fCollege”). Values may be other items, literals (dates, coordinates, etc.), or identifiers linking to external databases.  \n\n- **Sitelinks** – special links that connect an item to corresponding pages on client wikis (e.g., Wikipedia, Wikibooks, Wikiquote). They provide the bridge between the structured item and the human‑readable article.  \n\n**Interrelation**\n\n1. An **item** is the container for all its data.  \n2. The item’s **label**, **description**, and **aliases** give human‑readable names in multiple languages.  \n3. **Statements** are attached to the item; each statement uses a **property** to specify the type of claim and a **value** to supply the actual data.  \n4. **Properties** define the possible kinds of statements and may themselves link to external identifiers.  \n5. **Sitelinks** associate the item with external wiki pages, allowing client wikis to retrieve the latest structured data (labels, statements, etc.) for display.  \n\nThus, items are identified by Q‑numbers, described by multilingual text (labels, descriptions, aliases), characterized by property‑value statements, and linked to external wiki content via sitelinks.\n</result>', include_extracted_content_only_once=True, metadata=None, include_in_memory=False), ActionResult(is_done=True, success=True, error=None, attachments=[], long_term_memory='Task completed: True - The best way to learn about the structure and concepts of Wikidata, using only the Wikidata website, - 2357 more characters', extracted_content='The best way to learn about the structure and concepts of Wi